    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>It started with one tiny hic during the principal's speech. Ravi clapped a hand over his mouth, but it was too late. Hic. The microphone caught it. Hic. The whole auditorium heard.</p><p>A boy in the third row tried to help by yelling boo to scare them away. It did not work, but it did give the girl beside Ravi a fit of giggles that turned into her own hiccups. Soon hiccups were popping up across the rows like popcorn.</p><p>The principal, a wise woman who had seen many strange assemblies, simply smiled. She announced an impromptu Hiccup Championship. Whoever could hold their breath longest without hiccuping would win a homework pass.</p><p>The room went silent as two hundred kids puffed their cheeks. Faces turned pink. Eyes watered. One by one, hiccups burst out with squeaks and snorts, until only Ravi was left, cheeks ballooned, eyes streaming.</p><p>He made it to forty seconds before a giant hic shot out so loud the gym teacher applauded.</p><p>Ravi did not win the homework pass. But the principal gave him a special title anyway, scrawled on a paper certificate: Official Hiccup Champion, Most Honest Effort. He hung it on his wall, and to this day, whenever he gets the hiccups, he stands a little taller. After all, he is a champion.</p>",
