    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>The class president election had a problem: zero candidates. Mr. Owens stood at the board, marker uncapped, waiting. The silence stretched so long you could hear the clock judging everyone.</p><p>So Tara raised her hand and nominated Biscuit, her golden retriever, who happened to be the class pet for the week. Mr. Owens laughed, then realized she was serious, then wrote BISCUIT on the board because honestly, it was the only name.</p><p>The campaign was glorious. Biscuit's platform included longer recess, a snack drawer, and a strict no-homework-on-sunny-days policy. Tara made posters with paw prints. Biscuit shook hands with everyone using both front paws and won three votes purely by rolling over.</p><p>On election day, Biscuit won by a landslide. He celebrated by falling asleep on the podium.</p><p>Of course, a dog cannot truly be president. So Mr. Owens made Tara the official Vice President in Charge of Biscuit's Promises. Suddenly she had a job. She organized a real snack drawer, started a recess game club, and even convinced Mr. Owens to hold class outside on the sunniest Friday.</p><p>Biscuit napped through all of it, which the class agreed made him the most relaxed leader in school history. Tara realized she had wanted to lead all along. She just needed a very good dog to believe in her first.</p>",
