    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Sam asked for a normal birthday. His family heard backwards birthday, and there was no stopping them after that.</p><p>Guests arrived saying goodbye. The cake came out first, already with candles blown, so everyone un-sang the birthday song, which mostly sounded like humming in reverse. Presents were unwrapped by Sam and then wrapped up again to give back.</p><p>Dinner was dessert, then pizza, then a salad nobody touched, which Sam privately thought was the most honest part of the whole night. People walked backwards into walls. His aunt put her party hat on her chin.</p><p>Sam was mortified for exactly twenty minutes. Then his best friend high-fived him in slow reverse motion and he could not help it, he laughed.</p><p>By the end, the whole party was speaking in backwards sentences, and it had become the strangest, funniest night of the year. Photos showed everyone doing things in the wrong order, grinning like maniacs.</p><p>When the last guest hello-ed their way out the door, Sam flopped onto the couch, exhausted and happy. He admitted his family had been right. A normal party would have been forgotten by next week. This one, he would remember forever.</p><p>His mom kissed his forehead and whispered, happy birthday. Sam smiled and answered the only proper way. Birthday happy.</p>",
