    author: "Khyati Srivastava",
    slug: "the-last-tree-on-maple-street",
    category: "Drama",
    emoji: "🌳",
    excerpt: "When the city planned to cut down the oldest tree in the neighborhood, eleven-year-old Nora refused to let it go quietly.",
    created_at: "2026-04-24T18:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>The great oak on Maple Street had stood for a hundred years before Nora was born. It shaded her bedroom window and dropped acorns she had collected since she was four. Then a bright orange notice appeared on its trunk: scheduled for removal.</p><p>Nora did not cry, though she wanted to. Instead she knocked on doors. She learned the tree was being cut to widen the road, that nobody had really asked the neighborhood, that everyone assumed nothing could be done.</p><p>So she made it her business to ask. She gathered photographs, old and new, of children who had climbed those branches. She found her grandmother's wedding picture taken beneath it. She wrote a letter and read it, voice shaking, at the city meeting.</p><p>The room was quiet when she finished. An engineer admitted the road could curve slightly instead. A councilwoman said she had played under that tree as a girl and had forgotten until now.</p><p>The vote was close. The tree stayed.</p><p>On the first warm day after, Nora climbed to her favorite branch and looked out over the street she had fought for. The orange notice was gone. In its place, the neighbors had hung a small wooden sign she had painted herself.</p><p>It read simply: still standing, thanks to someone who asked. Nora leaned back against the rough, familiar bark and decided that some things were worth speaking up for, even when your voice shakes.</p>",
