    title: "Racing Against The Rain",
    author: "Khyati Srivastava",
    slug: "racing-against-the-rain",
    category: "Drama",
    emoji: "🏃",
    excerpt: "Dev had one chance to qualify for the championship, but the storm rolling in had other plans.",
    created_at: "2026-04-23T06:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Dev had trained all year for this single race. Qualify today, and he would run in the state championship. Miss it, and he would wait another twelve months. But dark clouds were stacking over the track, and the air smelled of coming rain.</p><p>The starter raised his hand. Dev settled into the blocks, heart pounding. Beside him, a runner named Theo, his fiercest rival, looked just as tense.</p><p>The gun fired. Dev exploded forward. The first lap felt smooth, the second harder. Then, on the third lap, the sky cracked open. Rain hammered down, slicking the track, blurring the lane lines. Runners began to slip.</p><p>Ahead of Dev, Theo's foot slid out from under him. He went down hard, sprawling across the wet track.</p><p>Dev had a choice he would replay for years. The finish line was close. So was Theo. He slowed, reached down, and hauled his rival to his feet.</p><p>They finished the last stretch together, soaked and gasping, neither one winning. Dev did not qualify that day.</p><p>But the officials had seen. So had the crowd. A week later, a letter arrived inviting Dev to the championship anyway, granted a special spot for showing what the sport was truly about. Theo had written a note too, just two words on the back of the envelope: thank you. Dev pinned it above his bed, prouder of that than any medal.</p>",
