    category: "Drama",
    emoji: "🏀",
    excerpt: "After the injury that nearly ended her season, Bella stepped to the free throw line with the game in her hands.",
    created_at: "2026-04-20T06:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Six months ago, Bella had torn a ligament and watched her team play from the bench, leg in a brace, heart in her throat. The doctors said she might not return at all. She returned anyway, slower, more careful, but back.</p><p>Now it was the final game of the season, the score tied, two seconds left. A foul sent Bella to the free throw line. The gym went silent. Two shots. The whole season balanced on them.</p><p>She bounced the ball, the way she had ten thousand times in physical therapy, the way she had practiced when her knee ached and she wanted to quit. She breathed. The first shot arced up and dropped clean through the net. The crowd roared. Her team was ahead by one.</p><p>The second shot did not matter for the win, but it mattered to her. She set her feet, the surgery scar pale on her knee, and released. The ball circled the rim once, twice, and fell in.</p><p>Her teammates swarmed her. But Bella stayed still for a moment, looking up at the ball settling in the net. She thought of every morning she had not given up, every painful exercise nobody saw.</p><p>The win was sweet. The real victory had happened months earlier, in an empty gym, when a girl with a hurt knee decided she was not finished yet. The free throws were just where everyone else got to see it.</p>",
