    excerpt: "Someone kept leaving notes in the margins of Iris's favorite library book, and she was determined to find out who.",
    created_at: "2026-04-19T12:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Iris checked out her favorite novel for the fourth time and found something new inside. Tiny pencil notes in the margins, written by someone who had clearly read it before her. This part always makes me laugh, said one. I hope she chooses to be brave here, said another, beside her own favorite chapter.</p><p>She wrote back. In light pencil, careful and shy, she added her own thoughts beneath theirs. Me too, she wrote. I read this part twice.</p><p>For weeks they passed the book back and forth through the library, two strangers having a whole conversation in the margins of a story. She learned the stranger loved rainy days and hated sad endings. He learned she always rooted for the underdog.</p><p>Iris started to wonder who he was. She would look up at the boys in the library and wonder, is it you, or you. She never asked the librarian. Some mysteries were too nice to spoil.</p><p>Then, on the very last page, beneath the final line of the book, she found a new note. If you have read this far with me, meet me in the poetry aisle on Friday at four. I will be holding a yellow umbrella, even though it is not raining.</p><p>On Friday, Iris walked to the poetry aisle, heart fluttering. A boy stood there, yellow umbrella in hand, cheeks pink. He smiled when he saw her. Hi, he said. I always hoped it would be you.</p>",
