    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>The spring fair glowed with paper lanterns, and a band played in the square while everyone danced. Everyone except Eli, who stood at the edge holding a lemonade he did not want, certain he would step on someone's feet if he tried.</p><p>He had come hoping to dance with Priya, a girl from his art class who laughed easily and drew the best dragons in the school. But every time he gathered his courage, it leaked right back out.</p><p>The song changed. Eli decided he would go home. He turned, and there was Priya, holding out her hand.</p><p>I saw you standing here, she said. I am terrible at dancing too. We can be terrible together.</p><p>So they were. They stepped on each other's feet and spun the wrong way and laughed every time they bumped into another couple. Eli forgot to be nervous. Priya twirled under the lanterns and her laughter was the best sound at the whole fair.</p><p>When the band slowed to a gentle song, they swayed in an awkward, happy circle. Priya told him she had hoped he would ask her, and had finally gotten tired of waiting.</p><p>I was scared, Eli admitted.</p><p>Me too, she said. That is why I came over.</p><p>They danced until the lanterns burned low and the band packed up. Walking home, Priya promised to teach him a proper step before next year. Eli already could not wait for the next spring fair.</p>",
