    category: "Kids",
    emoji: "🗺️",
    excerpt: "Theo finds a treasure map in the attic, but the compass rose is blank and the X could be anywhere.",
    created_at: "2026-04-12T00:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>In a dusty trunk, Theo found a hand-drawn map. It had wiggly trails, a duck pond, a crooked tree, and a bright red X. But the compass rose in the corner was blank, no north, no south, nothing.</p><p>How can I follow a map with no directions, Theo grumbled.</p><p>His grandfather chuckled from the doorway. I drew that map when I was your age, he said. The X is not a place you find by walking north. It is a place you find by remembering.</p><p>Confused, Theo studied the drawings. A duck pond. A crooked tree. He knew those. They were right here, in his grandfather's own backyard, just older and a little changed.</p><p>Together they walked outside. The pond was now a flower bed, the crooked tree taller and grayer. Theo paced to where the X should be and started to dig.</p><p>His shovel clinked against a rusted tin box. Inside lay a marble, a faded photo, and a note in a child's handwriting: To whoever finds this, the real treasure is the friend you dig with.</p><p>Theo looked up at his grandfather. They had been friends across fifty years, the boy who buried it and the boy who found it.</p>",
