    excerpt: "Quiet Ravi cannot sing or dance for the talent show, so he offers something nobody expected to need.",
    created_at: "2026-04-09T00:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>The talent show was coming, and everyone had a talent except Ravi, or so he thought. Mira could juggle. Sam could moonwalk. Pia played violin. Ravi could only do one thing well: he was good at noticing when people felt sad.</p><p>That is not a stage talent, he sighed.</p><p>The week before the show, things began to go wrong for the others. Mira dropped her juggling balls and burst into tears. Sam forgot his steps. Pia's hands shook so hard she could not hold her bow.</p><p>Ravi went to each of them. To Mira he said, Your hands are clever; one slip does not erase that. To Sam he said, You taught half the class that move; you already won. To Pia he said, I would rather hear three shaky notes from you than perfect ones from anybody else.</p><p>On show night, all three performed bravely, lifted by the words Ravi had given them.</p><p>When the host asked Ravi what his talent was, he froze. Then Mira shouted from the wings, He gives people their courage back. The others cheered.</p><p>Ravi did not win a trophy. But he learned that kind words, offered at the right moment, can be the most powerful act on any stage.</p>",
