    excerpt: "Jamie's bedroom mirror copies every move a few seconds too slow, and the reflection has something to say.",
    created_at: "2026-04-05T06:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Jamie noticed it on a quiet Sunday. When he waved at his bedroom mirror, the reflection waved back, but a few seconds too late, as if it had been daydreaming.</p><p>Most kids might have run. Jamie just leaned closer. Are you okay in there, he asked.</p><p>The reflection blinked, then slowly raised a hand and pressed it to the glass. On the foggy surface, letters appeared, written backward, slow and shaky: I am lonely.</p><p>Jamie understood. A mirror spends its whole life copying others and never gets to be itself.</p><p>So Jamie did something kind. Each evening he sat by the mirror and simply talked, telling jokes, sharing his day, no waving, no testing, just keeping it company. The reflection began to smile on its own, even when Jamie did not.</p><p>One night the reflection wrote a final message: Thank you for seeing me. Then, for the first time, it moved exactly in time with Jamie, a perfect, happy copy once more.</p><p>The strange delay never came back. But sometimes, late at night, Jamie would catch his reflection winking a half second early, as if sharing a secret only the two of them knew.</p>",
